    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>And Vive la Difference</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Greenstein letter notes that French people consider Worcestershire sauce sign of warped priorities of the English (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Worcestershire sauce may not have made it into ''Larousse Gastronomique,'' but it has certainly made it into the minds of the French.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Worcestershire sauce may not have made it into ''Larousse Gastronomique,'' but it has certainly made it into the minds of the French.</p>
        <p>Catholic in religion, catholic in gastronomy, French people consider this condiment a sign of the warped priorities across the Channel. More than 100 years ago, a Frenchman described England as ''a country with 60 religions and only one sauce.''</p>
        <p>DAVID GREENSTEIN  New York</p>
      </block>
